The random variables \(X\) and \(Y\) are independent, with \(X \sim N(5, 16)\) and \(Y \sim N(6, 9)\). The goal is to evaluate \(P(X > Y)\), which is equivalent to \(P(X - Y > 0)\).

Since \(X\) and \(Y\) are independent, the difference \(X - Y\) follows a normal distribution. The mean of \(X - Y\) is \(\mu_X - \mu_Y = 5 - 6 = -1\). The variance of \(X - Y\) is the sum of the variances: \(\sigma_X^2 + \sigma_Y^2 = 16 + 9 = 25\), so the standard deviation is \(\sqrt{25} = 5\). Thus, \(X - Y \sim N(-1, 25)\).

To find \(P(X - Y > 0)\), standardize the variable:  
\[
P\left( \frac{(X - Y) - (-1)}{5} > \frac{0 - (-1)}{5} \right) = P\left( Z > \frac{1}{5} \right) = P(Z > 0.2),
\]  
where \(Z\) is a standard normal random variable (\(Z \sim N(0, 1)\)).

Using the standard normal distribution, \(P(Z > 0.2) = 1 - P(Z \leq 0.2)\). From standard normal tables, \(P(Z \leq 0.2) \approx 0.5793\), so:  
\[
P(Z > 0.2) = 1 - 0.5793 = 0.4207.
\]  
Rounded to three significant figures, this is 0.421.

