Problem: 5.3-15. Three drugs are being tested for use as the treatment of a certain disease. Let $p_1, p_2$, and $p_3$ represent the probabilities of success for the respective drugs. As three patients come in, each is given one of the drugs in a random order. After $n=10$ "triples" and assuming independence, compute the probability that the maximum number of successes with one of the drugs exceeds eight if, in fact, $p_1=p_2=p_3=0.7$
 The unit of the answer should be  .
Solution: The problem requires finding the probability that the maximum number of successes for one of the three drugs exceeds 8, given that each drug has a success probability of 0.7 and there are 10 independent triples (each triple tests all three drugs once).

Each drug follows a binomial distribution with parameters \(n = 10\) and \(p = 0.7\). The probability that the maximum number of successes for any drug exceeds 8 is equivalent to the probability that at least one drug has more than 8 successes (i.e., 9 or 10 successes).

First, compute the probability that a single drug has more than 8 successes:
- \(P(X_i = 9) = \binom{10}{9} (0.7)^9 (0.3)^1 = 10 \times (0.7)^9 \times 0.3 = 0.121060821\)
- \(P(X_i = 10) = \binom{10}{10} (0.7)^{10} (0.3)^0 = (0.7)^{10} = 0.0282475249\)
- \(P(X_i > 8) = P(X_i = 9) + P(X_i = 10) = 0.121060821 + 0.0282475249 = 0.1493083459\)

The probability that a single drug has at most 8 successes is:
- \(P(X_i \leq 8) = 1 - P(X_i > 8) = 1 - 0.1493083459 = 0.8506916541\)

Since the drugs are independent, the probability that all three drugs have at most 8 successes is:
- \(P(\text{all } X_i \leq 8) = [P(X_i \leq 8)]^3 = (0.8506916541)^3 = 0.615625377\)

The probability that at least one drug has more than 8 successes is:
- \(P(\max > 8) = 1 - P(\text{all } X_i \leq 8) = 1 - 0.615625377 = 0.384374623\)

Rounding to three significant figures, the result is 0.384.

