- For \(X \leq \frac{1}{3}\), the shorter segment is \(X\) and the longer is \(1-X\), so \(1-X \geq 2X\).
- For \(X \geq \frac{2}{3}\), the shorter segment is \(1-X\) and the longer is \(X\), so \(X \geq 2(1-X)\).

The probability is the measure of the favorable intervals divided by the total length. The intervals \([0, \frac{1}{3}]\) and \([\frac{2}{3}, 1]\) each have length \(\frac{1}{3}\), so the combined length is \(\frac{2}{3}\). The total length is 1, so the probability is \(\frac{2}{3}\).

Rounded to three decimal places, \(\frac{2}{3} \approx 0.667\).

