Solution: The ground-state energy of positronium is calculated based on the reduced mass of the electron-positron system. Since both particles have the same mass \(m_e\), the reduced mass \(\mu = \frac{m_e}{2}\). The ground-state energy for a hydrogen-like atom is proportional to the reduced mass. For hydrogen, with \(\mu \approx m_e\), the energy is \(-13.6 \, \text{eV}\). For positronium, with \(\mu = \frac{m_e}{2}\), the energy is half of that of hydrogen, resulting in \(-6.8 \, \text{eV}\).

